06954nam a22008775i 9786155211508DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20082008hu     fo  d z      eng d  a9786155211508  a(DE-B1597)633612  a(OCoLC)1338020184  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 7aSOC0110002bisacsh00aWitchcraft Mythologies and Persecutions /ced. by Gábor Klaniczay, Éva Pócs. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (358 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDemons, Spirits, Witches00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Mythologies -- tThe Concept of the Witches’ Sabbath in the Alpine Region (1430–1440) Text and Context -- tRound-table discussion with Carlo Ginzburg, Gustav Henningsen, Éva Pócs, Giovanni Pizza and Gábor Klaniczay -- tLearned Systems and Popular Narratives of Vision and Bewitchment -- tLate Medieval Witch Mythologies in the Balkans -- tChild Witches and the Construction of the Witches’ Sabbath: The Swedish Blåkulla Story -- tPart II. Legal Mechanisms, Social Contexts -- tPart II Legal Mechanisms, Social Contexts River Ordeal—Trial by Water—Swimming of Witches: Procedures of Ordeal in Witch Trials -- tHow to Make a (Legal) Pact with the Devil? Legal Customs and Literacy in Witch Confessions in Early Modern Hungary -- tHealing at the Jagiellonian Court -- tFollowing the Traces of Xenophobia in Muscovite Witchcraft Investigation Records -- tTrial of an Honest Citizen in Nagybánya 1704–1705; A Tentative Microanalysis of Witchcraft Accusations -- tBoundaries and Transgressions: Witchcraft and Community Conflict in Estonia During the Late Nineteenth Century -- tPart III. Witchcraft and Folklore -- tExtraordinary Children, Werewolves, and Witches in Portuguese Folk Tradition -- tReflections of Folk Belief and Legends at the Witch Trials of Estonia -- tWitches and Priests in the Bulgarian Village: Past and Present -- tWitchcraft in Eastern Slovenia -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis third, concluding volume of the series publishes 14 studies and the transcription of a round-table discussion on Carlo Ginzburg's Ecstasies. The themes of the previous two volumes, Communicating with the Spirits, and Christian Demonology and Popular Mythology, are further expanded here both as regards their interdisciplinary approach and the wide range of regional comparisons. While the emphasis of the second volume was on current popular belief and folklore as seen in the context of the historical sources on demonology, this volume approaches its subject from the point of view of historical anthropology. The greatest recent advances of witchcraft research occurred recently in two fields: (1) deciphering the variety of myths and the complexity of historical processes which lead to the formation of the witches' Sabbath, (2) the micro-historical analysis of the social, religious, legal and cultural milieu where witchcraft accusations and persecutions developed. These two themes are completed by some further insights into the folklore of the concerned regions which still carries the traces of the traumatic historical memories of witchcraft persecutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aDemonologyzEuropexHistoryvCongresses. 0aFolklorezEuropexHistoryvCongresses. 0aWitchcraftzEuropexHistoryvCongresses. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Folklore & Mythology.2bisacsh  aConference, Demonology, Folklore, Persecutions, Witchcraft.1 aAngusheva, Adelina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrzezińska, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGinzburg, Carlo, e